{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"089a6595-a1f6-431e-80c3-c6ad980d2fc1","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar/ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container) or copy the tool binary in.\n- For flame-graph style output, add `--format speedscope`.\n- If you need OS-level context (native frames, kernel), use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling` or fall back to `perf record -g -p <PID>` (requires `SYS_ADMIN` / privileged).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a866765-2f38-4f14-8367-df384c3a5e7e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":350,"requestId":"5025:3B0A41:1F17147:2382F13:69F551D1"},"id":"9f7e07b4-c2f9-433b-911a-64a8c8b0543b","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:22:35.584Z","parentId":"b7c30297-e943-4652-9193-66eed56cdc75"}
